	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Divergent trends within South Africa’s cereals sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The February 2011 USDA review of the grain and feed sector in South Africa identifies different trends in the wheat and maize sectors. The 2010/11 South African wheat crop is estimated to be down 23% on the 2009/10 season, at 1.511 million tonnes. This is a result of a 15% decline in the area under wheat. Since deregulation in 1997, wheat farmers have faced a serious profitability squeeze, with a continuous decline in real prices and a constant increase in costs. Imports at 1.6m tonnes will account for ‘more than half of domestic demand’ in 2010/11. Production, however, is expected to bounce back to a limited degree in the 2011/12 season in response to high global wheat prices.</p><p>In the 2009/10 marketing year, most of South Africa’s wheat imports originated in Germany (63%). However, in the four months from 1 October 2010 to 21 January 2011 only 7% of South African wheat imports originated in Germany, with the USA picking up the slack. In 2009/10, ‘South Africa exported 320,519 tons of wheat from its own stocks to neighbouring countries … and 109,841 tons of imported wheat.’</p><p>In the face of the difficulties faced in the wheat sector, South African wheat producers have sought greater tariff protection, which has only partially been conceded by the Tariff Board.</p><p>In the maize sector, three years of bumper harvests have left South Africa with large stocks. Maize yields continue to improve in South Africa, with the 2010/11 crop up 6.8% on the previous year. Logistical constraints, however, limit export possibilities, despite the high world prices of maize and the recent weakening in the value of the rand. USDA estimates that South Africa has around 4m tonnes of maize available for export ‘excluding pipeline corn’, but expects only 1.7m tonnes to be exported, with good harvests elsewhere in the region limiting export opportunities. The local over-supply generated by this is exerting a downward pressure on maize prices on SACU markets. This is seeing some substitution of maize products for wheat products in the context of rising wheat prices.</p><p>While total exports are currently dominated by yellow maize for use as animal feed (62.4%), regional markets largely consist of white maize exports for human consumption. Indeed, the SACU market dominates white maize exports (58.1% in the 2011 season), with 17.4% exported to neighbouring Mozambique and Zimbabwe. South African exports dominate the neighbouring SACU markets.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
USDA Foreign Agricultural Service, ‘South Africa: Grain and feed annual’, <i>GAIN</i>&nbsp;report, 11 February 2011<br />

<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed%20Annual_Pretoria_South%20Africa%20-%20Republic%20of_2-11-2011.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Grain%20and%20Feed...</a>&nbsp;<br />
<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Export snags leave South Africa wallowing in corn’, 18 February 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/export-snags-leave-south-africa-wallowing-in-corn--2840.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/export-snags-leave-south-africa-wallowing-...</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Developments in the South African cereals sector have a wider than domestic significance, since South Africa dominates regional cereals production and trade, either on the basis of domestic production (white maize) or re-exports (i.e. imports of wheat which are subsequently re-exported to markets in the SADC region). This dominance, which is compounded by a growing South African corporate presence in the retail sector, creates problems in moving towards regional free trade in cereals products, with a range of non-tariff barriers in place in the region.</p><p>While South African maize production has been expanding, there are fears that the logistical problems faced in finding markets could generate a profitability squeeze which will see the current expansive trend reversed.</p><p>The decline in wheat exports from Germany to South Africa may reflect the opening up of opportunities for EU exporters closer to home, following the introduction of an export ban by Russia. EU wheat exporters have been losing markets in the Middle East and North Africa for some years. The Russian export ban, however, appears to have helped EU companies to recapture some of these markets, with French wheat exporters doing particularly well.</p><p>With EU wheat exports projected to be around 17% down on 2009 levels up to 2020, the question arises as to how reliable a wheat supplier the EU will be in the coming years. This raises questions about the appropriate trade policies to be pursued in the cereals sector in ACP countries of the region in the context of a trend towards rising prices and increased price volatility.</p>
		</div>
		
